<tr>
	<td class="alt1" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Elured</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Die, Die And Go To Hell<br />
	
	<br /><img src="image.php?s=ae28a2a678c396101216431a19397979&amp;userid=18940&amp;dateline=1043773681" border="0" alt="Avatar" title="Elured's Avatar" hspace="4" vspace="4" /><br />
	<br />
	Joined: May 2002<br />
	Location: The Handbasket
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt1" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>So, lets take some "average" examples of what a player could expect out of a fairly reasonable "non-raid" time in EverQuest, before and after LDoN.<br />
<br />
Tae Ew tunic is a good old standard from before LDoN.  Not too expensive, pretty good stats.  60 HP's on the thing.<br />
<br />
A ranger with Askr's Thunderous Breastplate, from Time, has 210 HP on his chest.<br />
<br />
Now, fast forward to today.  So far, the best augment found for Type 8 chest HP is the Gauntlet Stone of Fortitude, +70 HP, dropping in a <u><b>raid</b></u> setting.  It's Lore, so you're only getting one.  That's a 33% increase in HP for your chest slot.<br />
<br />
With LDoN, the Tae Ew equipped ranger who spends his time to get "the best," is going to go from 60 HP to 140 HP.  That's over 100% better.  It doesn't even really take that long to get the points if you're 65; you get 30-50 points for what amount to standard grinds in any old zone, but here you're getting very nice rare drops (Stained Axe, etc.) *and* points that give you access to some of the best gear you'll ever see.<br />
<br />
Lets be generous and say you could afford a Farwater Scale BP before LDoN came out.  With a +40 augment from LDoN that's 160 HP, an increase of 33%.  This increase is exactly the same as the Time person.  You're not that far from an unaugmented Askr's BP; that kind of thing can last you until you <i>do</i> see PoT.<br />
<br />
Is your time less valuable than the raider's?  YES!  Raiding is harder than a simple group.  Sure, 5-10 people do the real work, and 60 or so just do what they're told; but they wouldn't be sitting there being told what to do if the loot wasn't better than what they'd get single-grouping.  That's the whole damn point!<br />
<br />
If the people who "did the hardest work" were always the ones to get the best gear, then you, and I, and everyone else would probably have a lot of lesser gear than we now do.  I wasn't performing at my level best when I looted my Sebilite Scale Leggings in OS back in the day; there was a monk pulling, an enchanter mezzing, an uber ranger tanking...I just had to sit there and add my damage.  That's the way a lot of things end up working in EverQuest, and in real life.</p>
	
	
	
		<div>__________________<br />Surprisingly, I was wrong; which really isn't all that unusual, but it still manages to surprise me every time.</div>
	
