<tr>
	<td class="alt1" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>forsaken</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Tree Huggin Hippy Ranger<br />
	
	
	<br />
	Joined: Dec 1999<br />
	Location: A forest nearby.
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt1" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Renwin Everfool</b><br /><i><br />
<br />
Oh, you don't have the "time" to devote to proper feed and care of your Risk? Well. We have something here - good for beginners, or people with <b>real lives</b> (/shudder - dirty words).<br />
Enjoy!</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>Let's not pretend raiding is somehow all that high risk. The main risk from what I can see is one of more people spending as a group more time together for a possible failure. It's more to do with group risk than individual risk, a small group without someone to do a CR handy runs a lot more individual risk than a raid with a plethoria of classes to chose from as potential resources.<br />
<br />
I'm not saying raiding is easy, or that it can't be time consuming, obviously it can be both hard and time consuming much of the time. But there can easily be more real risk in a small group encounter, or soloing, than can be found on a raid, and higher levels of risk are more common outside of raids too. <br />
<br />
I'm not saying that the risk vs. reward is unbalanced between raiding and non-raiding either, just it's more like comparing apples and oranges, they're both fruit, but they both are utterly different beyond that in many key respects.<br />
<br />
When looking at risk vs reward in different gaming scenarios you've got to stick to the basics, and avoid some of the but-but rationalizations and justifications, otherwise invalid comparisons grow like weeds in mound of crap that's been composted and left in the sun long enough to have the bad smell covered over. Real basics too;<br />
<br />
1. Did you gain exp<br />
2. Did you die and get a rez<br />
3. Did you die and not get a rez.<br />
4. How much time did you spend at the activity.<br />
5. Was time invested in the activity lost due to failure.<br />
6. Was time outside of the activity lost due to failure (CR's etc.)<br />
<br />
Stuff like that, very fundemental factors... It may well be that the apple is less of a reward proportionatly than the orange. It may well be that via one method, the reward is not proportionatly as good as that from another method, but that the other method offers higher risk... Or, that a reward in terms of risk vs. reward has lower proportions but is otherwise unavailible outside of that gaming scenario. That last is pretty common in EQ for whatever activity you're doing.<br />
<br />
The list of basics goes on, but the thing is we don't often discuss it in those terms, and that's something of a mistake. As is belittling the efforts in the game of anyone.<br />
<br />
Personaly, I've been wholey unimpressed with a lot of what goes with raiding, but other things, like coordination, do impress me. It's that mixed bag thing having to do with what makes the types of play dissimilar. <br />
<br />
But to imply that somehow someone's better just cause they do one or the other is one of the most annoying and ludicrous characterizations that plague discussions where this stuff comes up.<br />
<br />
<br />
-F</p>
	
	
	
		<div>__________________<br />Those Orcs never learn do they.</div>
	
	
