<tr>
	<td class="alt1" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Sunil</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Senior Member<br />
	
	
	<br />
	Joined: Jan 2000<br />
	Location: NV
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt1" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>I'm not going to call it risk vs. reward, because, like someone else said, risk is relative.<br />
<br />
It's all about time investment and commitment, just like it always has been with EQ.  If you want to be mad about someone getting more, better gear faster than you, be mad at the guy who started 3 months ago, levelled up to 65 with 100 AA's, and then joined an already time-enabled guild.  He probably got better gear in the week it took him to get flagged than you'll ever see (assuming you don't follow his path).<br />
<br />
But who can you really blame?  Him, for taking adantage of a well-known opportunity?  The guild he joined for making it so easy on him?  Or...yourself, for not taking the same opportunity?<br />
<br />
Also, the benefit from common LDoN augs is much more marginal for a raiding player than for a casual player.  40 hps added to a 200 hp item is a 20% increase, where 40 hps added to a 50 hp item is an 80% increase.  If you and your friends deck out your gear with commonly available augs, your ability and survivability in your current encounters increase dramatically (to the point of probably making them trivial), while the time-level raider sees a far smaller increase in the same.  Yet, because of the nature of the two different people, the time-level raider is more likely to actually do it.</p>
	
	
	
		<div>__________________<br />Hunter <b><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=318080" target="_blank">Sunil Sturmritter</a></b><br />
Forest Stalker of Karana<br />
Bertoxx</div>
	
	
