<tr>
	<td class="alt1" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Myrea</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Investigating Ranger<br />
	
	<br /><img src="image.php?s=ae28a2a678c396101216431a19397979&amp;userid=9869&amp;dateline=1023027310" border="0" alt="Avatar" title="Myrea's Avatar" hspace="4" vspace="4" /><br />
	<br />
	Joined: Jul 2000<br />
	Location: Centennial, CO, USA
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt1" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>There's never going to be a balance between raiders who spend 50+ hours per week in this game and people who spend less than 20. It's not possible, and I've come to realize that's the way it should be. <br />
<br />
I used to resent that my friends without kids could play twice as much as me and they had levels and gears I couldn't even begin to think about. It wasn't fair that they could be so uber, but I never had a chance because I don't have a 15 hour block of my life EVER that I can dedicate to elemental level raids.<br />
<br />
There are 2 things that have made it possible for me to steadily level and improve my gear. The Bazaar made it possible to actually sell some of the things I collect without dedicating endless boring hours to auctions, and to buy things I need or want. That was a tremendous boon to casual players that made us more able to, if not compete, at least be a presence. Secondly, LDON made XP pickup groups easier to find, and gave us a possiblity of rewards actually fitting our level.<br />
<br />
People who don't raid are never going to match the gear and XP of people who do. It's a fact that casual players have to live with, but our lot in life has imporved decidedly.</p>
	
	
	
