<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Tetrass</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Senior Member<br />
	
	
	<br />
	Joined: Aug 2000<br />
	
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Katalaeia</b><br /><i>I think if non-raider A puts in 5 hours a day earning LDoN points and time-raider B puts in 5 hours a day raiding Time, the effort is the same. Both are working toward a goal. Eventually A will get that shiny new bp/sword/augmentation and B will kill Quarm. How is one's "work" any less valuable than the other? Goals are RELATIVE, guys. Player B's 5 hours a day is exactly the same effort as player A's. All that is different is what those hours are applied toward.<br />
<br />
Now...<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
Caddyshack quote!! I love that movie.<br />
<br />
"Pick up that blood!"</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>I really have to disagree with you here.  A player spending 5 hours doing LDoN missions is not putting out the same amount of effort as someone who is raiding.<br />
<br />
At various points during the last 4 years I have been guildless for maybe 1.5 years, I've been in a casual guild that raided once in a while, I've been in a guild that raided 4 nights a week (officially, realistically it was every day,) and now I'm back with a casual guild that raids 2 - 3 times a week.<br />
<br />
The only things that raiding and doing LDoN adventures have in common are that you have to be playing EQ if you want to do them both.  Raiding takes a commitment to other players, a commitment to be in a certain virtual place at a certain real-world time.  Raiding means that you will frequently be targetting mobs whose only benefit is to somebody else, but that helps the guild so you do it.  Raiding means being prepared to stay online way way longer than originally planned if a nasty CR has to be completed (at least pre-PoP that is.)  Raiding means doing things that take more than one group to accomplish, and the harder the targets you want to go after, the larger the group it takes (as a general thing, simply because of how each expansion was designed.)<br />
<br />
LDoN requires none of that.  I don't have to commit to a certain time; I can log on at 11pm and spend five hours doing LDoN.  I can do 5 hours of LDoN with total strangers.  I don't have to commit to a certain place; I can prioritize which LDoN themes I want to do on an individual basis because I don't need to be concerned with what anyone else needs.  I don't even need to be in a guild to get equipment that is only surpassed by Elemental and Time quality gear.<br />
<br />
If you want equipment that comes from raid encounters, then you have to raid.  This is how the game has been since the days when Vox and Naggy were the toughest mobs on the block.  The people who spend their time killing the toughest mobs under the most constraining conditions deserve to get the best equipment.  Nobody is preventing anyone from dedicating their time and energy to meeting the requirements and commitment required by a high-end raiding guild.  Now maybe that's not possible or even desirable for many people due to RL or any number of other reasons, but the option is there.  Honestly I think casual players (like I am myself once again) should be damn happy that LDoN even exists.<br />
<br />
This whole thread boils down to one thing: envy.</p>
	
	
	
		<div>__________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=22240">Hunter Tetrass</a><br />
Forest Stalker(65)<br />
<br />
<br />
Innoruuk Server</div>
	
	
